Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Line a #baking sheet{} with foil and brush with @vegetable oil{1%tsp} or coat with nonstick spray. Wash and dry all produce.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @red onion{1}; mince a few slices until you have 1 TBSP (2 TBSP for 4 servings).

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add sliced onion; cook for ~{3%minutes}.

Stir in @ground beef{10%oz}; cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and onion is softened, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir in @Tex-Mex paste{1} and @water{1/3%cup} (½ cup for 4 servings). Simmer until mixture is thickened and beef is cooked through, ~{2-4%minutes}. Turn off heat.

Meanwhile, drizzle @flour tortillas{6} with @olive oil{1%tbsp} (2 TBSP for 4 servings); brush or rub to completely coat.

Place tortillas on a clean work surface. Once beef filling is done, add a heaping ¼ cup filling to one side of each tortilla, then sprinkle with 1 TBSP @Mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup}. Roll up tortillas, starting with filled sides, to create flautas. Place seam sides down on prepared sheet.

> Make sure the flautas are snug on the sheet—this will prevent them from unrolling.

Bake on middle rack until golden brown and crispy, ~{8-12%minutes}.

== Pico de Gallo ==

While flautas bake, finely dice @Roma tomato{1}. Zest and quarter @lime{1}. In a #small bowl{}, combine tomato, minced onion, half the lime zest, and a squeeze of lime juice. Season with @salt{}.

== Lime Crema ==

In a separate small bowl, combine @sour cream{4%tbsp}, remaining lime zest, and a squeeze of lime juice. Add @water{1%tsp} 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with @salt{}.

== Assembly ==

Divide flautas between plates. Top with pico de gallo, lime crema, and @guacamole{4%tbsp}. Serve.